(7, 'Building a Personal Blog in Vanilla PHP: Lessons from a 300-Level CS Student in Nigeria', 'building-a-personal-blog-in-vanilla-php-lessons-from-a-300-level-cs-student-in-nigeria', 'uploads/readwithken.png', 'Screenshots', '<p>As a 300-level Computer Science student juggling courses like Data Structures, Operating Systems, and System Analysis, I never thought I\'d spend my SIWES placement building something from scratch that feels truly mine. But here I am, deep into creating a personal blogging platform using pure PHP and MySQL—no frameworks, no Laravel or WordPress crutches. Just vanilla code, one file at a time. It\'s been frustrating, eye-opening, and honestly, one of the most rewarding things I\'ve done in my tech journey so far.</p><p>Why vanilla PHP? In a world where everyone pushes React, Node.js, or fancy stacks, going back to basics felt like the right challenge. Nigeria\'s tech scene is booming—startups in Lagos are raising millions, and AI tools are everywhere—but many entry-level opportunities still revolve around maintaining legacy PHP systems. Companies like banks, e-commerce sites, and even government portals run on PHP. Learning it deeply means I\'m preparing for real-world jobs, not just trendy bootcamp projects. Plus, with data costs and unreliable electricity, keeping things lightweight matters. No heavy dependencies crashing because of a bad network.</p><p>The project started simple: a basic CRUD system for posts. Create a post with title, content, and image upload. Read it on the frontend. Update via an edit page. Delete with confirmation. Sounds straightforward, right? But implementing it taught me more than any textbook. First hurdle: file uploads. I had to handle $_FILES properly, check MIME types to prevent malicious uploads, and move files to a secure directory. One bug let me upload anything—scary when thinking about security. I fixed it by validating extensions and using uniqid() for filenames.</p><p>Then came the database side. Early on, I was concatenating user input directly into queries. Classic mistake. A lightbulb moment hit when I read about SQL injection—attackers could drop tables with a sneaky comment. I refactored everything to prepared statements. It\'s slower to write, but way safer.</p><p>Simple, but it blocks injections cold. I also added input sanitization with trim(), stripslashes(), and htmlspecialchars() to fight XSS. Security isn\'t optional; in Nigeria, where cyber threats are rising, building secure apps from day one is crucial.</p><p>The admin dashboard was next. A login system with sessions—hash passwords with password_hash(), verify with password_verify(). Separate pages for managing posts, but I reorganized: moved headers, navbars, and footers into an \"includes\" folder. Cleaner code, less repetition. Git became my best friend for tracking changes, especially when deploying to free hosting like InfinityFree.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\"></p><p>Challenges? Plenty. InfinityFree\'s limits meant optimizing queries—no heavy loops. Image handling bugs when files didn\'t exist (fixed with file_exists()). And deployment woes: Chrome flagging the site as \"unsafe\" because of HTTP instead of HTTPS. Working fix: focusing on functionality first.</p><p>But the real magic? Seeing it live. Adding a newsletter feature—subscribers\' emails stored in a separate table, manual sending from the dashboard. It\'s basic, but imagining real readers subscribing feels huge.</p><p>This project bridges theory and practice. Data Structures? Understanding arrays for post lists. Operating Systems? Thinking about file handling and processes.</p><p>For fellow Nigerian CS students: start small. Build something personal. Vanilla PHP teaches patience and fundamentals that frameworks hide. In 2026, with AI exploding (Nigeria leads global adoption in some rankings), knowing core web dev lets you integrate tools like Grok or Claude for code help without losing control.</p><p>I\'m not done yet—next: better frontend rendering, pagination, maybe search. But already, this blog feels like a portfolio piece. If you\'re in 300-level or SIWES, try it. The wahala is worth it.</p>', '2026-02-05 15:24:50');

